A4.text: Along with the soleus muscle, the gastrocnemius forms half of the calf muscle.

A5.text: The gastrocnemius is primarily involved in running, jumping and other 'fast' movements of leg, and to a lesser degree in walking and standing.

A6.text: The triceps surae consists of two muscles located at the calf â€“ the two-headed gastrocnemius and the soleus.

A7.text: The deep (profundus) mass of muscle (the soleus) forms the remaining head which attaches to the superior posterior area of the tibia.

A8.text: In humans and some other mammals, the soleus is a powerful muscle in the back part of the lower leg (the calf).

A9.text: The soleus is the most effective muscle for plantar flexion in a bent knee position.
